00:44:56.340 --> 00:44:58.670
through another constitutional
convention.

00:44:58.670 --> 00:45:00.220
Cynthia disagrees.

00:45:00.220 --> 00:45:01.680
&gt;&gt; Cynthia Levinson:
I think it's nuts.

00:45:01.680 --> 00:45:04.100
The framers have
absolutely no idea

00:45:04.100 --> 00:45:05.760
of how this would take place.

00:45:05.760 --> 00:45:10.240
They just said there could
be another way to do this.

00:45:10.240 --> 00:45:12.990
There's no way to know how
they delegates would be chosen,

00:45:12.990 --> 00:45:15.400
what authority they have.

00:45:15.400 --> 00:45:18.270
You may have specific
issues you don't

00:45:18.270 --> 00:45:21.240
like about the Constitution
or not, you know,

00:45:21.240 --> 00:45:24.240
a couple of groups said our
country's been fine so far.

00:45:24.240 --> 00:45:26.350
Well there was this
matter of the Civil War.

00:45:26.350 --> 00:45:29.820
But, except for that
and some other things,

00:45:29.820 --> 00:45:32.480
you might think the
Constitution's fine in general

00:45:32.480 --> 00:45:34.460
but have a couple
specific questions,

00:45:34.460 --> 00:45:37.140
maybe about the Second
Amendment for instance.

00:45:37.140 --> 00:45:39.520
But, there's no way to,
once you open it up,

00:45:39.520 --> 00:45:41.260
once you have a constitutional
convention,

00:45:41.260 --> 00:45:44.110
just the way the framers
completely overturned the

00:45:44.110 --> 00:45:45.950
Articles of Confederation,

00:45:45.950 --> 00:45:48.540
the whole thing could
be up for grabs.

00:45:48.540 --> 00:45:51.370
I would say we might risk
losing the First Amendment,

00:45:51.370 --> 00:45:52.670
Freedom of Speech.

00:45:52.670 --> 00:45:54.550
Sandy thinks that
wouldn't happen.

00:45:54.550 --> 00:45:56.210
But, who knows?

00:45:56.210 --> 00:45:58.260
So, I just think it's too risky.

00:45:58.260 --> 00:46:00.070
And, that's the debate,
basically,

00:46:00.070 --> 00:46:01.800
that we have going
back and forth

00:46:01.800 --> 00:46:03.320
in the last chapter of the book.

00:46:03.320 --> 00:46:04.910
Second to the last chapter.

00:46:04.910 --> 00:46:06.620
In the last chapter, actually,

00:46:06.620 --> 00:46:09.160
we give the Constitution
a grade.

00:46:09.160 --> 00:46:12.440
And, we invite you, as
you read through the book,

00:46:12.440 --> 00:46:16.270
to think about what your grade
for the Constitution would be.

00:46:16.270 --> 00:46:20.000
We based it on our device,
our guidelines for how

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:23.220
to judge the Constitution
is the preamble.

00:46:23.220 --> 00:46:26.210
So, we invite you to look
closely at the preamble

00:46:26.210 --> 00:46:29.590
as the values basis
for the Constitution

00:46:29.590 --> 00:46:30.910
and grade it according

00:46:30.910 --> 00:46:34.920
to how well you think
it meets those goals

00:46:34.920 --> 00:46:36.650
for the Constitution.

00:46:36.650 --> 00:46:38.680
We would love, there
may be another end here

00:46:38.680 --> 00:46:40.620
by the library people,
we would love to know

00:46:40.620 --> 00:46:42.570
if you have any ideas
for our blog.

00:46:42.570 --> 00:46:43.980
We blog twice a month.

00:46:43.980 --> 00:46:46.960
We're going to ask your
teacher's librarians over here

00:46:46.960 --> 00:46:49.010
if they would like to
sign up for the blog.

00:46:49.010 --> 00:46:50.310
And, we would like your ideas

00:46:50.310 --> 00:46:53.900
so that our next blog would
be, can come from you.

00:46:53.900 --> 00:46:55.780
&gt;&gt; Lee Ann Potter: On behalf
of the Library of Congress,

00:46:55.780 --> 00:46:59.020
we are so happy that you were
able to come this morning

00:46:59.020 --> 00:47:03.170
and that you participated
as actively as you did.

00:47:03.170 --> 00:47:06.510
I can't tell you how
exciting it is really, I mean,

00:47:06.510 --> 00:47:09.480
young people talking about our
Constitution is exactly what

00:47:09.480 --> 00:47:10.780
needs to be happening.

00:47:10.780 --> 00:47:12.080
And, the fact that we were doing

00:47:12.080 --> 00:47:13.740
that today makes me
very, very happy.

00:47:13.740 --> 00:47:15.680
And, I hope you had a, I hope
you had fun at the library.

00:47:15.680 --> 00:47:19.000
The Library of Congress can be a
pretty imposing and scary place.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:20.460
And, we don't want it to be.

00:47:20.460 --> 00:47:22.560
We want it to be a
really welcoming place.

00:47:22.560 --> 00:47:25.370
We want it to be a place
where you are excited to come

00:47:25.370 --> 00:47:28.040
and that you want to come and
not only participate in programs

00:47:28.040 --> 00:47:31.210
